title=Drop Post}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=a}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Disney+}}\n{{Disney}}\n\n[[Category:2020 computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:Disney animated short films]]\n", "name_user": "Jchjw", "label": "safe", "comment": "added link to Tangelene Bolton", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Short_Circuit_(short_series)"}
{"title_page": "The Offence", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2014}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = The Offence\n| image =Poster of the movie The Offence.jpg\n| caption =Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Sidney Lumet]]\n| producer = [[Denis O'Dell]]\t\n| writer = [[John Hopkins (writer)|John Hopkins]] (play and screenplay)\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Sean Connery]]\n* [[Trevor Howard]]\n* [[Vivien Merchant]]\n* [[Ian Bannen]]}}\n| music =[[Harrison Birtwistle]]\n| cinematography = [[Gerry Fisher]]\n| editing = John Victor-Smith\n| studio = Tantallon\n| distributor = [[United Artists]]\n| released = {{film date|1973|1|11|df=y}}\n| runtime = 112 minutes\n| country = United Kingdom\n| language = English\n| budget = $900,000<ref name=\"bray\">{{cite book|first=Christopher|last=Bray|title=Sean Connery: The Measure of a Man|publisher=[[Faber and Faber]]|location=London, England|date=2010|ISBN=9780-571-23807-1|pages=174\u2013180}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''The Offence''''' is a 1973 British [[crime film|crime]] [[neo noir]] [[drama film]] directed by [[Sidney Lumet]], based upon the 1968 stage play ''This Story of Yours'' by [[John Hopkins (writer)|John Hopkins]].<ref name=\"bray\" /> It stars [[Sean Connery]] as police [[detective]] Johnson, who kills suspected [[child molester]] Kenneth Baxter ([[Ian Bannen]]) while interrogating him. The film explores Johnson's varied, often aggressive attempts at rationalizing what he did, revealing his true motives for killing the suspect in a series of flashbacks. [[Trevor Howard]] and [[Vivien Merchant]] appear in major supporting roles.\n\n==Plot ==\nDetective-Sergeant Johnson has been a police officer for 20 years and is deeply affected by the [[murder]]s, [[rape]]s, and other violent crimes he has investigated. He is plagued by images of violence and is losing his mind under the strain.\n\nHis anger surfaces while interrogating Kenneth Baxter, who is suspected of raping a young girl. By the end of the interrogation, Johnson has severely beaten Baxter who is then taken to the hospital where he later dies. Johnson is suspended for the beating and returns home for the night, getting into a violent argument with his wife Maureen. Two of Johnsons colleagues comes to inform him that Baxter died in hospital and that Johnson must come to the station right away.\n\nThe following day, Johnson is interviewed by Detective Superintendent Cartwright. During their long confrontation, [[flashback (literary technique)|flashbacks]] show the events of the previous night, when Johnson beats Baxter.\n\nThe flashbacks portray Baxter - whose guilt or innocence is left ambiguous - taunting Johnson, insinuating that he secretly wants to commit the sort of [[sex crime]]s he investigates. Johnson at first flies into a rage and strikes Baxter, but he eventually admits that he does indeed harbour obsessive fantasies of murder and rape. He then tearfully begs Baxter to help him. When Baxter recoils from him in disgust, Johnson snaps and kills him.\n\nThe film ends with another flashback, this time of Johnson attacking the police officers who pulled him off Baxter, and muttering \"God...my God...\" as he realises what he has done.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Sean Connery]] - Johnson\n*[[Trevor Howard]] - Cartwright\n*[[Vivien Merchant]] - Maureen\n*[[Ian Bannen]] - Baxter\n*[[Peter Bowles]] - Cameron\n*[[Derek Newark]] - Jessard\n*[[Ronald Radd]] - Lawson\n*[[John Hallam]] - Panton\n*[[Richard Moore (actor)|Richard Moore]] - Garrett\n*[[Anthony Sagar]] - Hill\n*[[Maxine Gordon]] - Janie\n*[[Hilda Fenemore]] - woman on common  \n*Rhoda Lewis - woman at school  \n*Cynthia Lund - child at school  \n*[[Howard Goorney]] - Lambert\n\n==Production==\n{{refimprove section|date=March 2016}}\nWhen Connery agreed to return as [[James Bond]] in ''[[Diamonds Are Forever (film)|Diamonds Are Forever]]'', [[David V. Picker]], CEO of [[United Artists]], pledged to back two of Connery's own film projects, provided they cost $2&nbsp;million or less, in association with Connery's own production company, Tantallon Films.<ref>Alan Barnes and Marcus Hearn, ''Kiss Kiss Bang Bang: The Unofficial James Bond Film Companion'', BT Batsford Ltd, London 1997, page 99</ref>  ''The Offence'', made under the working title ''Something Like the Truth'' (a line that appears in [[John Hopkins (writer)|John Hopkins]]' original play), was the first. Connery was keen to shake off the image of James Bond and expand his range as an actor.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jun/14/the-offence-sidney-lumet-dvd-review-sean-connery</ref>\n\nConnery had previously worked with Hopkins when the writer had co-scripted ''[[Thunderball (film)|Thunderball]]'' and had seen the play during its original run in London in 1968. Seeing potential in the story, Connery bought the option on the film rights and asked Hopkins to adapt the script for the big screen. <ref>http://www.londonpubtheatres.com/this-story-of-yours/4594169452</ref>\n\nHaving made two films with Sidney Lumet, ''[[The Hill (film)|The Hill]]''  and ''[[The Anderson Tapes]]'' Connery appreciated his straightforward approach and offered him the job of directing. Lumet was keen to work with Connery again and accepted. Ian Bannen, who had also appeared in ''The Hill'' was hired as co-star.<ref>http://screenanarchy.com/2015/05/learning-from-the-masters-of-cinema-sidney-lumets-the-offence.html</ref>\n\nThe film was shot on a small budget of \u00a3385,000 in March and April 1972 in and around [[Bracknell]], [[Berkshire]] - notably the [[Wildridings]] Mill Pond area and [[Easthampstead]]'s Point Royal. Interior sets were filmed at Twickenham Studios.<ref name=\"bray\" /> The fight sequences between Connery and Bannen were choreographed, uncredited, by [[Bob Simmons (stunt man)|Bob Simmons]], who had designed similar action scenes for the Bond films. The film remains Sir [[Harrison Birtwistle]]'s only film score.<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=T83Z0vkHWBcC&pg=PA125&lpg=PA125&dq=tantallon+films#v=onepage&q=tantallon%20films&f=false |title = The Films of Sean Connery|isbn = 9780806522234|last1 = Pfeiffer|first1 = Lee|last2 = Lisa|first2 = Philip|year = 2001}}</ref>\n\nUnited Artists released ''The Offence'' early in 1973. It was a critical success but a commercial failure and did not yield a profit for nine years,<ref name=\"bray\" /> even going unreleased in several markets, including [[France]], where it did not premiere until 2007. United Artists pulled out of the deal and the other project, a film version of ''[[Macbeth]]'' that Connery was to direct, was scotched by [[Roman Polanski]]'s [[Macbeth (1971 film)|adaptation]].\n\n==Reception==\n{{blockquote|\"A fascinating look at the human [[Psyche (psychology)|psyche]] based on ''[[Z-Cars|Z Cars]]'' scriptwriter John Hopkins acclaimed stage play ''This Story of Yours'', ''The Offence'' is an expertly crafted study of [[evil]] and human weakness that demands to be watched in its entirety. ''[...]'' it still packs quite a punch and features compelling performances from both Sean Connery and Ian Bannen.\"|Britmovie}}\n\n{{blockquote|\"Less well-known than his other British pictures (''[[The Hill (film)|The Hill]]'', ''[[The Deadly Affair]]'', ''[[Murder on the Orient Express (1974 film)|Murder on the Orient Express]]''), this unrelentingly somber policier inaugurates a newfound force in Lumet\u2019s work. The story, adapted by John Hopkins from his play, abounds in stylistic tics (recurring visual [[Motif (visual arts)|motif]]s, various events replayed several times, [[color coding]]), but the flashiness that pockmarked much of the director\u2019s earlier work has been pruned to hushed, concentrated intensity. Likewise, the movie looks ahead to the bathed-in-gray themes of Lumet\u2019s later studies of law & order ambivalence -- Connery\u2019s pressure-cooker copper, plagued with lurid images palpitating inside his brain, is the template for the protagonists of ''[[Serpico]]'', ''[[Prince of the City]]'' and ''[[Q&A (film)|Q & A]]''. Connery pinpoints some fantastic shadings of bullying, dissatisfaction and self-disgust, matched by Bannen\u2019s peerless razzing &mdash; the culminating pounding is less liberating purgation than guilt transference, christened by Bannen\u2019s bloodied leer.\"|Fernando F. Croce, Cinepassion}}\n\n==DVD releases==\nIn 2004, [[MGM]] [[UK]] released a [[DVD]] of the film which contained no extras or trailers. Simultaneous releases from MGM were made in other [[PAL]] format countries, such as [[Germany]] and [[Australia]]. On 20 October 2008, the film was again released on DVD in the UK by [[Optimum Releasing]], again without extras or trailers. A French [[DVD region code#2|Region 2]] DVD, preserving the film's original ratio of 1:1.66, became available in 2009. In April 2010, MGM put the film out on a U.S. DVD-R \"on demand\" for the first time. It is available as an exclusive from Amazon.com and contains no extras.\n\nIn 2014 the film was released on [[Blu-ray]] in the US, and in 2015 it was released in the UK in the same format.\n\n==This Story of Yours==\n[[John Hopkins (writer)|John Hopkins]]' original play, ''This Story of Yours'', takes the form of three duologues between Johnson and, in Act One, Maureen, then Cartwright in Act Two and Baxter in Act Three. Directed by [[Christopher Morahan]], it opened at London's [[Royal Court Theatre]] on 11 December 1968. The cast was as follows:<ref>''Who's Who in the Theatre'' (15th edition), Pitman Publishing, London 1972, page 155</ref>\n\n*Johnson - [[Michael Bryant (actor)|Michael Bryant]]\n*Maureen - [[Alethea Charlton]]\n*Cartwright - [[John Phillips (actor)|John Phillips]]\n*Baxter - [[Gordon Jackson (actor)|Gordon Jackson]]\n*Policemen - Edward Clayton, Steven Barnes, Oliver Maguire, Colin Pinney\n\nThe first major revival of the play was directed by [[Jack Gold]] at London's [[Hampstead Theatre]], opening on 5 February 1987 with the following cast:<ref>''This Story of Yours'' a play by John Hopkins / Hampstead Theatre: programme by Stilwell Darby & Co Ltd: '1987 no 7'</ref>\n\n*Johnson - [[David Suchet]]\n*Maureen - Jane Wood\n*Cartwright - [[Bryan Pringle]]\n*Baxter - [[James Hazeldine]]\n*Det Sgt Jessard - Richard Cubison\n*Police Constables - Paul Fryer, Frederick Lane\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0070468|title=The Offence}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|offence}}\n* [http://www.ecranlarge.com/movie_video-view-4438-831.php Original theatrical trailer] for ''The Offence''\n\n{{John Hopkins}}\n{{Sidney Lumet}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Offence, The}}\n[[Category:1973 films]]\n[[Category:1970s crime drama films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British crime drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:British films based on plays]]\n[[Category:United Artists films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Sidney Lumet]]\n[[Category:Films about child sexual abuse]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by John Hopkins]]\n\n[[ru:\u041e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0440\u0431\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2014}}\n{{refimprove|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = The Offence\n| image =Poster of the movie The Offence.jpg\n| caption =Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Sidney Lumet]]\n| producer = [[Denis O'Dell]]\t\n| writer = [[John Hopkins (writer)|John Hopkins]] (play and screenplay)\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Sean Connery]]\n* [[Trevor Howard]]\n* [[Vivien Merchant]]\n* [[Ian Bannen]]}}\n| music =[[Harrison Birtwistle]]\n| cinematography = [[Gerry Fisher]]\n| editing = John Victor-Smith\n| studio = Tantallon\n| distributor = [[United Artists]]\n| released = {{film date|1973|1|11|df=y}}\n| runtime = 112 minutes\n| country = United Kingdom\n| language = English\n| budget = $900,000<ref name=\"bray\">{{cite book|first=Christopher|last=Bray|title=Sean Connery: The Measure of a Man|publisher=[[Faber and Faber]]|location=London, England|date=2010|ISBN=9780-571-23807-1|pages=174\u2013180}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''The Offence''''' is a 1973 British [[crime film|crime]] [[neo noir]] [[drama film]] directed by [[Sidney Lumet]], based upon the 1968 stage play ''This Story of Yours'' by [[John Hopkins (writer)|John Hopkins]].<ref name=\"bray\" /> It stars [[Sean Connery]] as police [[detective]] Johnson, who kills suspected [[child molester]] Kenneth Baxter ([[Ian Bannen]]) while interrogating him. The film explores Johnson's varied, often aggressive attempts at rationalizing what he did, revealing his true motives for killing the suspect in a series of flashbacks. [[Trevor Howard]] and [[Vivien Merchant]] appear in major supporting roles.\n\n==Plot ==\nDetective-Sergeant Johnson has been a police officer for 20 years and is deeply affected by the [[murder]]s, [[rape]]s, and other violent crimes he has investigated. He is plagued by images of violence and is losing his mind under the strain.\n\nHis anger surfaces while interrogating Kenneth Baxter, who is suspected of raping a young girl. By the end of the interrogation, Johnson has severally beaten Baxter who is then taken to the hospital where he later dies. Johnson is suspended for the beating and returns home for the night, getting into a violent argument with his wife Maureen. Two of Johnsons colleagues comes to inform him that Baxter died in hospital and that Johnson must come to the station right away.\n\nThe following day, Johnson is interviewed by Detective Superintendent Cartwright. During their long confrontation, [[flashback (literary technique)|flashbacks]] show the events of the previous night, when Johnson beats Baxter.\n\nThe flashbacks portray Baxter - whose guilt or innocence is left ambiguous - taunting Johnson, insinuating that he secretly wants to commit the sort of [[sex crime]]s he investigates. Johnson at first flies into a rage and strikes Baxter, but he eventually admits that he does indeed harbour obsessive fantasies of murder and rape. He then tearfully begs Baxter to help him. When Baxter recoils from him in disgust, Johnson snaps and kills him.\n\nThe film ends with another flashback, this time of Johnson attacking the police officers who pulled him off Baxter, and muttering \"God...my God...\" as he realises what he has done.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Sean Connery]] - Johnson\n*[[Trevor Howard]] - Cartwright\n*[[Vivien Merchant]] - Maureen\n*[[Ian Bannen]] - Baxter\n*[[Peter Bowles]] - Cameron\n*[[Derek Newark]] - Jessard\n*[[Ronald Radd]] - Lawson\n*[[John Hallam]] - Panton\n*[[Richard Moore (actor)|Richard Moore]] - Garrett\n*[[Anthony Sagar]] - Hill\n*[[Maxine Gordon]] - Janie\n*[[Hilda Fenemore]] - woman on common  \n*Rhoda Lewis - woman at school  \n*Cynthia Lund - child at school  \n*[[Howard Goorney]] - Lambert\n\n==Production==\n{{refimprove section|date=March 2016}}\nWhen Connery agreed to return as [[James Bond]] in ''[[Diamonds Are Forever (film)|Diamonds Are Forever]]'', [[David V. Picker]], CEO of [[United Artists]], pledged to back two of Connery's own film projects, provided they cost $2&nbsp;million or less, in association with Connery's own production company, Tantallon Films.<ref>Alan Barnes and Marcus Hearn, ''Kiss Kiss Bang Bang: The Unofficial James Bond Film Companion'', BT Batsford Ltd, London 1997, page 99</ref>  ''The Offence'', made under the working title ''Something Like the Truth'' (a line that appears in [[John Hopkins (writer)|John Hopkins]]' original play), was the first. Connery was keen to shake off the image of James Bond and expand his range as an actor.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jun/14/the-offence-sidney-lumet-dvd-review-sean-connery</ref>\n\nConnery had previously worked with Hopkins when the writer had co-scripted ''[[Thunderball (film)|Thunderball]]'' and had seen the play during its original run in London in 1968. Seeing potential in the story, Connery bought the option on the film rights and asked Hopkins to adapt the script for the big screen. <ref>http://www.londonpubtheatres.com/this-story-of-yours/4594169452</ref>\n\nHaving made two films with Sidney Lumet, ''[[The Hill (film)|The Hill]]''  and ''[[The Anderson Tapes]]'' Connery appreciated his straightforward approach and offered him the job of directing. Lumet was keen to work with Connery again and accepted. Ian Bannen, who had also appeared in ''The Hill'' was hired as co-star.<ref>http://screenanarchy.com/2015/05/learning-from-the-masters-of-cinema-sidney-lumets-the-offence.html</ref>\n\nThe film was shot on a small budget of \u00a3385,000 in March and April 1972 in and around [[Bracknell]], [[Berkshire]] - notably the [[Wildridings]] Mill Pond area and [[Easthampstead]]'s Point Royal. Interior sets were filmed at Twickenham Studios.<ref name=\"bray\" /> The fight sequences between Connery and Bannen were choreographed, uncredited, by [[Bob Simmons (stunt man)|Bob Simmons]], who had designed similar action scenes for the Bond films. The film remains Sir [[Harrison Birtwistle]]'s only film score.<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.com/?id=T83Z0vkHWBcC&pg=PA125&lpg=PA125&dq=tantallon+films#v=onepage&q=tantallon%20films&f=false |title = The Films of Sean Connery|isbn = 9780806522234|last1 = Pfeiffer|first1 = Lee|last2 = Lisa|first2 = Philip|year = 2001}}</ref>\n\nUnited Artists released ''The Offence'' early in 1973. It was a critical success but a commercial failure and did not yield a profit for nine years,<ref name=\"bray\" /> even going unreleased in several markets, including [[France]], where it did not premiere until 2007. United Artists pulled out of the deal and the other project, a film version of ''[[Macbeth]]'' that Connery was to direct, was scotched by [[Roman Polanski]]'s [[Macbeth (1971 film)|adaptation]].\n\n==Reception==\n{{blockquote|\"A fascinating look at the human [[Psyche (psychology)|psyche]] based on ''[[Z-Cars|Z Cars]]'' scriptwriter John Hopkins acclaimed stage play ''This Story of Yours'', ''The Offence'' is an expertly crafted study of [[evil]] and human weakness that demands to be watched in its entirety. ''[...]'' it still packs quite a punch and features compelling performances from both Sean Connery and Ian Bannen.\"|Britmovie}}\n\n{{blockquote|\"Less well-known than his other British pictures (''[[The Hill (film)|The Hill]]'', ''[[The Deadly Affair]]'', ''[[Murder on the Orient Express (1974 film)|Murder on the Orient Express]]''), this unrelentingly somber policier inaugurates a newfound force in Lumet\u2019s work. The story, adapted by John Hopkins from his play, abounds in stylistic tics (recurring visual [[Motif (visual arts)|motif]]s, various events replayed several times, [[color coding]]), but the flashiness that pockmarked much of the director\u2019s earlier work has been pruned to hushed, concentrated intensity. Likewise, the movie looks ahead to the bathed-in-gray themes of Lumet\u2019s later studies of law & order ambivalence -- Connery\u2019s pressure-cooker copper, plagued with lurid images palpitating inside his brain, is the template for the protagonists of ''[[Serpico]]'', ''[[Prince of the City]]'' and ''[[Q&A (film)|Q & A]]''. Connery pinpoints some fantastic shadings of bullying, dissatisfaction and self-disgust, matched by Bannen\u2019s peerless razzing &mdash; the culminating pounding is less liberating purgation than guilt transference, christened by Bannen\u2019s bloodied leer.\"|Fernando F. Croce, Cinepassion}}\n\n==DVD releases==\nIn 2004, [[MGM]] [[UK]] released a [[DVD]] of the film which contained no extras or trailers. Simultaneous releases from MGM were made in other [[PAL]] format countries, such as [[Germany]] and [[Australia]]. On 20 October 2008, the film was again released on DVD in the UK by [[Optimum Releasing]], again without extras or trailers. A French [[DVD region code#2|Region 2]] DVD, preserving the film's original ratio of 1:1.66, became available in 2009. In April 2010, MGM put the film out on a U.S. DVD-R \"on demand\" for the first time. It is available as an exclusive from Amazon.com and contains no extras.\n\nIn 2014 the film was released on [[Blu-ray]] in the US, and in 2015 it was released in the UK in the same format.\n\n==This Story of Yours==\n[[John Hopkins (writer)|John Hopkins]]' original play, ''This Story of Yours'', takes the form of three duologues between Johnson and, in Act One, Maureen, then Cartwright in Act Two and Baxter in Act Three. Directed by [[Christopher Morahan]], it opened at London's [[Royal Court Theatre]] on 11 December 1968. The cast was as follows:<ref>''Who's Who in the Theatre'' (15th edition), Pitman Publishing, London 1972, page 155</ref>\n\n*Johnson - [[Michael Bryant (actor)|Michael Bryant]]\n*Maureen - [[Alethea Charlton]]\n*Cartwright - [[John Phillips (actor)|John Phillips]]\n*Baxter - [[Gordon Jackson (actor)|Gordon Jackson]]\n*Policemen - Edward Clayton, Steven Barnes, Oliver Maguire, Colin Pinney\n\nThe first major revival of the play was directed by [[Jack Gold]] at London's [[Hampstead Theatre]], opening on 5 February 1987 with the following cast:<ref>''This Story of Yours'' a play by John Hopkins / Hampstead Theatre: programme by Stilwell Darby & Co Ltd: '1987 no 7'</ref>\n\n*Johnson - [[David Suchet]]\n*Maureen - Jane Wood\n*Cartwright - [[Bryan Pringle]]\n*Baxter - [[James Hazeldine]]\n*Det Sgt Jessard - Richard Cubison\n*Police Constables - Paul Fryer, Frederick Lane\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0070468|title=The Offence}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|offence}}\n* [http://www.ecranlarge.com/movie_video-view-4438-831.php Original theatrical trailer] for ''The Offence''\n\n{{John Hopkins}}\n{{Sidney Lumet}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Offence, The}}\n[[Category:1973 films]]\n[[Category:1970s crime drama films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British crime drama films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:British films based on plays]]\n[[Category:United Artists films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Sidney Lumet]]\n[[Category:Films about child sexual abuse]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by John Hopkins]]\n\n[[ru:\u041e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0440\u0431\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot:fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Offence"}
{"title_page": "J\u0101nis L\u0101\u010dpl\u0113sis", "text_new": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name                = J\u0101nis L\u0101\u010dpl\u0113sis\n| image               = J\u0101nis L\u0101\u010dpl\u0113sis.jpg\n| office              = [[Mayor of Daugavpils]]\n| term_start1         = 28 September 2009\n| term_start2         = 1 July 2013\n| term_end1           = 24 March 2011\n| term_end2           = 26 June 2017\n| predecessor1        = [[Rihards Eigims]]\n| predecessor2        = \u017danna Kulakova\n| successor1          = [[\u017danna Kulakova]]\n| successor2          = [[Andrejs Elksni\u0146\u0161]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1958|10|8}}\n| birth_place         = [[Daugavpils]], [[Latvia]]\n| party               = [[Latvian Way]]<br>[[Latvia's First Party/Latvian Way]]<br>[[Latgale Party]]\n| alma_mater          = [[Riga Technical University]]\n}}\n\n'''J\u0101nis L\u0101\u010dpl\u0113sis''' (born 8 October 1958 in [[Daugavpils]]) is Latvian financier, politician and former mayor of [[Daugavpils]] (2009-2011, 2013-2017). He was a member of the [[Saeima|Latvian parliament]] during the [[7th Saeima]] and the [[11th Saeima]].<ref>http://www.tvnet.lv/zinas/regionos/280421-par_daugavpils_jauno_meru_ievelets_janis_lacplesis</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat-inline}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lacplesis, Janis}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Daugavpils]]\n[[Category:Latvian Way politicians]]\n[[Category:Latvia's First Party/Latvian Way politicians]]\n[[Category:Latgale Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 7th Saeima]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 11th Saeima]]\n[[Category:Riga Technical University alumni]]\n\n\n{{Latvia-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n|name        = J\u0101nis L\u0101\u010dpl\u0113sis\n|image       = J\u0101nis L\u0101\u010dpl\u0113sis.jpg\n|office      = [[Mayor of Daugavpils]]\n|term_start1 = 28 September 2009\n|term_start2 = 1 July 2013\n|term_end1   = 24 March 2011\n|term_end2   = 26 June 2017\n|predecessor1 = [[Rihards Eigims]]\n|predecessor2 = \u017danna Kulakova\n|successor1   = [[\u017danna Kulakova]]\n|successor2   = [[Andrejs Elksni\u0146\u0161]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1958|10|8}}\n|birth_place = [[Daugavpils]], [[Latvia]] \n|party       = [[Latvian Way]], [[Latvia's First Party/Latvian Way]], [[Latgale Party]]\n|alma_mater  = [[Riga Technical University]]\n}}\n\n'''J\u0101nis L\u0101\u010dpl\u0113sis''' (born 8 October 1958 in [[Daugavpils]]) is Latvian financier, politician and former mayor of [[Daugavpils]] (2009-2011, 2013-2017). He was a member of the [[Saeima|Latvian parliament]] during the [[7th Saeima]] and the [[11th Saeima]].<ref>http://www.tvnet.lv/zinas/regionos/280421-par_daugavpils_jauno_meru_ievelets_janis_lacplesis</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat-inline}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lacplesis, Janis}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Daugavpils]]\n[[Category:Latvian Way politicians]]\n[[Category:Latvia's First Party/Latvian Way politicians]]\n[[Category:Latgale Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 7th Saeima]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 11th Saeima]]\n[[Category:Riga Technical University alumni]]\n\n\n{{Latvia-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ivario", "label": "safe", "comment": "style", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J%C4%81nis_L%C4%81%C4%8Dpl%C4%93sis"}
{"title_page": "Eurovision Song Contest 2021", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox song contest\n| name = Eurovision Song Contest\n| year = 2021\n| logo = Eurovision Song Contest.svg\n| semi1 = \n| semi2 = \n| final = \n| presenters = \n| director = \n| exsupervisor = [[Martin \u00d6sterdahl]]\n| producer = \n| writer = \n| winner = {{Esc|Belarus|y=2020}} 'Da Vidna'\n| vote = \n| host = \n| venue = \n| entries = <!-- Reserve this field for when the final list of participants is announced by the EBU -->\n| debut = <!-- Reserve this field for when the final list of participants is announced by the EBU -->\n| return = <!-- Reserve this field for when the final list of participants is announced by the EBU -->\n| nonreturn = <!-- Reserve this field for when the final list of participants is announced by the EBU -->\n| null = \n| interval = \n| opening = \n<!-- Map Legend Colours \u2013 Please do not add country names to this section, it will not change the map. -->\n| Green = \n| Green SA = Y\n| Purple = Y\n| Red = \n| Yellow = Y\n}}\n\nThe '''Eurovision Song Contest 2021''' is set to be the 65th edition of the [[Eurovision Song Contest]]. Following the cancellation of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2020]], the organising [[European Broadcasting Union]] (EBU) is discussing carryovers from the 2020 contest, such as host city and participating artists, with various parties.\n\n== Format ==\n\n=== Location ===\nFollowing the cancellation of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2020]], the organising [[European Broadcasting Union]] (EBU) is in talks with Dutch broadcasters [[AVROTROS]], [[Nederlandse Publieke Omroep (organization)|NPO]] and [[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting|NOS]], as well as the city of [[Rotterdam]], which were to organise the 2020 contest, on the possibility of staging the 2021 contest in the city.<ref name=\"2020 cancellation statement\">{{cite web |url=https://eurovision.tv/official-ebu-statement-and-faq-eurovision-song-contest-2020-cancellation |title=Official EBU statement & FAQ on Eurovision 2020 cancellation |date=18 March 2020 |website=[[Eurovision.tv]] |access-date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318142008/https://eurovision.tv/official-ebu-statement-and-faq-eurovision-song-contest-2020-cancellation |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Executive supervisor ===\nIn January 2020, the EBU announced that [[Martin \u00d6sterdahl]] would become the executive supervisor for the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] after the 2020 edition, succeeding [[Jon Ola Sand]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eurovision.tv/story/martin-osterdahl-new-eurovision-song-contest-executive-supervisor |title=Martin \u00d6sterdahl new Eurovision Song Contest Executive Supervisor |date=20 January 2020 |website=[[Eurovision.tv]]}}</ref> Before his appointment, \u00d6sterdahl had been an [[executive producer]] for the {{Escyr|2013}} and {{Escyr|2016}} editions, and had been a member of the Eurovision Song Contest reference group between 2012 and 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eurovoix.com/2020/01/20/martin-osterdahl-appointed-eurovision-executive-supervisor/ |title=Martin \u00d6sterdahl Appointed Eurovision Executive Supervisor |first=Neil |last=Farren |date=20 January 2020 |website=Eurovoix |access-date=20 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318204303/https://eurovoix.com/2020/01/20/martin-osterdahl-appointed-eurovision-executive-supervisor/ |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Entries ===\nFollowing the cancellation of the 2020 contest, the EBU explored the option of allowing the songs selected for the 2020 contest to compete in the 2021 contest, which would need to be discussed with the Eurovision Song Contest reference group and the national broadcasters.<ref name=\"2020 cancellation statement\" /> [[Victoria Georgieva|Victoria]], the planned participant for Bulgaria in 2020, publicly expressed her support for such a move.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eurovisionworld.com/esc/the-favorit-to-win-eurovision-2020-we-should-be-allowed-to-perform-our-songs-in-2021 |title=The favourite to win Eurovision 2020: \"We should be allowed to perform our songs in 2021\" |author=Rasmus |date=18 March 2020 |website=Eurovisionworld |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320102431/https://eurovisionworld.com/esc/the-favorit-to-win-eurovision-2020-we-should-be-allowed-to-perform-our-songs-in-2021 |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> However, on 20 March 2020, the reference group decided that, in accordance with the [[rules of the Eurovision Song Contest]], the 2020 songs would not be eligible to compete in the 2021 contest.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eurovision.tv/story/intention-to-honour-eurovision-2020-songs-artists |title=Intention to honour Eurovision 2020 songs and artists |date=20 March 2020 |website=[[Eurovision.tv]] |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320195055/https://eurovision.tv/story/intention-to-honour-eurovision-2020-songs-artists |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Opening and interval acts ===\n[[Lenny Kuhr]], one of the winners of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1969]], stated she would perform at the 2021 contest. She was previously slated to perform in the 2020 edition before it was cancelled.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=LenKuhr |number=1242239936658649094 |title=Ik doe ook weer mee op Eurovision 2021 in Rotterdam! Bijna alle concerten die in maart, april en mei niet door konden gaan zijn verplaatst naar volgend seizoen. Houdt anderhalve meter afstand dan komt alles goed. |first=Lenny |last=Kuhr |author-link=Lenny Kuhr |date=24 March 2020 |language=nl}}</ref>\n\n== Participating countries ==\n\n=== Returning artists ===\nAfter the cancellation of the 2020 contest, multiple participating broadcasters announced that for the 2021 contest they would internally select the same artists initially selected for 2020: Australia, Austria, Azerbaijan, Belgium, Bulgaria, Georgia, Greece, Israel, Netherlands, Romania, Spain, Switzerland and Ukraine.<ref name=\"confirmed_2020artists\">{{cite web |url=https://eurovision.tv/story/these-artists-are-already-confirmed-for-eurovision-2021 |title=These artists are already confirmed for Eurovision 2021 |date=23 March 2020 |website=[[Eurovision.tv]] |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323182536/https://eurovision.tv/story/these-artists-are-already-confirmed-for-eurovision-2021 |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Stefania Liberakakis|Stefania]] represented the {{Esccnty|Netherlands|Junior|y=2016}} in the [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2016]] as part of the group [[Netherlands in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2016#Kisses|Kisses]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://wiwibloggs.com/2020/02/03/confirmed-stefania-represent-greece-eurovision-2020-supergirl/249074/ |title=Confirmed! Stefania will represent Greece at Eurovision 2020 with \"SUPERGIRL\" |first=Robyn |last=Gallagher |date=3 February 2020 |website=[[Wiwibloggs]] |access-date=3 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203195452/https://wiwibloggs.com/2020/02/03/confirmed-stefania-represent-greece-eurovision-2020-supergirl/249074/ |archive-date=3 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Vincent Bueno]] provided backing vocals for [[Nathan Trent]] for {{Esccnty|Austria|y=2017}} in {{Escyr|2017}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://escxtra.com/2020/03/26/vincent-bueno-2021/ |title=\ud83c\udde6\ud83c\uddf9 Vincent Bueno to return to represent Austria in 2021 |first=Tom |last=Ryan |date=26 March 2020 |website=ESCXtra |access-date=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326154809/https://escxtra.com/2020/03/26/vincent-bueno-2021/ |archive-date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Provisional list of participating countries ===\nThe following countries have confirmed their intent to participate in the 2021 contest.\n<!--Please do not add confirmations that took place before 18 March because of the unique situation concerning the cancellation of Eurovision 2020 -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Country\n! Artist<ref name=\"confirmed_2020artists\" />\n! Song\n! Language(s)\n|-\n| {{Esc|Australia}}\n| [[Montaigne (musician)|Montaigne]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sbs.com.au/programs/eurovision/article/2020/04/01/montaigne-represent-australia-eurovision-song-contest-2021 |title=Montaigne to represent Australia at the Eurovision Song Contest 2021 |date=2 April 2020 |website=[[Special Broadcasting Service]] |access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Austria}}\n| [[Vincent Bueno]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eurovoix.com/2020/03/26/austria-vincent-bueno-eurovision/ |title=Austria: Vincent Bueno to Eurovision 2021 |first=Emily |last=Herbert |date=26 March 2020 |website=Eurovoix |access-date=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326143507/https://eurovoix.com/2020/03/26/austria-vincent-bueno-eurovision/ |archive-date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Azerbaijan}}\n| [[Samira Efendi|Efendi]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Belgium}}\n| [[Hooverphonic]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Bulgaria}}\n| [[Victoria Georgieva|Victoria]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Croatia}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hrtprikazuje.hrt.hr/593786/za-eurosong-2021-morat-ce-biti-odabrane-nove-pjesme |title=Za Eurosong 2021. morat \u0107e biti odabrane nove pjesme |language=hr |author=Komunikacije HRT-a |date=21 March 2020 |website=[[Hrvatska radiotelevizija]] |access-date=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321131742/https://hrtprikazuje.hrt.hr/593786/za-eurosong-2021-morat-ce-biti-odabrane-nove-pjesme |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Denmark}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dr.dk/musik/foerst-blev-eurovision-aflyst-nu-kommer-der-alligevel-et-show |title=F\u00f8rst blev Eurovision aflyst. Nu kommer der alligevel et show |language=da |first1=Kasper |last1=Madsb\u00f8ll Christensen |first2=Christian |last2=Mejdahl |date=3 April 2020 |website=[[Danmarks Radio]] |access-date=3 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321131742/https://www.dr.dk/musik/foerst-blev-eurovision-aflyst-nu-kommer-der-alligevel-et-show |archive-date=3 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Estonia}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eurovoix.com/2020/03/18/estonia-eesti-laul-will-determine-eurovision-2021-participant/ |title=Estonia: Eesti Laul Will Determine Eurovision 2021 Participant |first=Anthony |last=Granger |date=18 March 2020 |website=Eurovoix |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320102154/https://eurovoix.com/2020/03/18/estonia-eesti-laul-will-determine-eurovision-2021-participant/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Finland}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://esctoday.com/179527/finland-yle-confirms-participation-in-eurovision-2021-umk-2021-confirmed/ |title=Finland: YLE confirms participation in Eurovision 2021; UMK 2021 confirmed |first=Sanjay (Sergio) |last=Jiandani |date=25 March 2020 |website=ESCToday |access-date=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326113843/http://esctoday.com/179527/finland-yle-confirms-participation-in-eurovision-2021-umk-2021-confirmed/ |archive-date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Georgia}}\n| [[Tornike Kipiani]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Greece}}\n| [[Stefania Liberakakis|Stefania]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Ireland}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://escxtra.com/2020/03/21/ireland-eurovision-2021/ |title=RT\u00c9 confirm intentions to take part in Eurovision 2021 |first=Tom |last=Ryan |date=21 March 2020 |website=ESCXtra |access-date=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321124945/https://escxtra.com/2020/03/21/ireland-eurovision-2021/ |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Israel}}\n| [[Eden Alene]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Lithuania}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lrt.lt/en/news-in-english/19/1157011/lithuania-to-pick-new-song-for-next-year-s-eurovision |title=Lithuania to pick new song for next year's Eurovision |date=31 March 2020 |website=[[Lithuanian National Radio and Television]]}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Netherlands}}\n| [[Jeangu Macrooy]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Norway}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://esctoday.com/179543/norway-nrk-confirms-participation-in-eurovision-2021-mgp-confirmed/ |title=Norway: NRK confirms participation in Eurovision 2021: MGP confirmed |first=Sanjay |last=Jiandani |date=26 March 2020 |website=ESCToday |access-date=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326113838/http://esctoday.com/179543/norway-nrk-confirms-participation-in-eurovision-2021-mgp-confirmed/ |archive-date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Romania}}\n| [[Roxen (singer)|Roxen]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://esctoday.com/179596/romania-tvr-confirms-roxen-as-2021-romanian-eurovision-hopeful/ |title=Romania: TVR confirms Roxen as 2021 Romanian Eurovision hopeful |first=Sanjay |last=Jiandani |date=31 March 2020 |website=ESCToday}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Spain}}\n| [[Blas Cant\u00f3]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Sweden}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eurovisionworld.com/esc/sweden-2021-new-representative-to-be-selected-from-melodifestivalen/ |title=Sweden: New artist and song to be selected from Melodifestivalen 2021 |first=Steven |last=Spiteri |date=18 March 2020 |website=Eurovisionworld}}</ref>\n| \n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Switzerland}}\n| [[Gjon's Tears]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Ukraine}}\n| [[Go_A]]\n|\n|\n|}\n\n== Other countries ==\n{{Further|List of countries in the Eurovision Song Contest}}\nEligibility for potential participation in the Eurovision Song Contest requires a national broadcaster with [[European Broadcasting Union#Members|active EBU membership]] that will be able to broadcast the contest via the [[Eurovision (network)|Eurovision network]]. The EBU will issue an invitation of participation in the contest to all active members. In contrast to previous years, associate member {{Esccnty|Australia}} does not need an invitation for the 2021 contest, as it had previously been granted permission to participate at least until 2023.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/australia-secures-spot-in-eurovision-until-2023|title=Australia secures spot in Eurovision for the next five years|last=Groot|first=Evert|date=12 February 2019|website=[[Eurovision.tv]]|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213045839/https://eurovision.tv/story/australia-secures-spot-in-eurovision-until-2023|archive-date=13 February 2019|access-date=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Active EBU members ===\n* {{Esc|Andorra}} \u2013 In November 2019, [[Democrats for Andorra]], the ruling party of Andorra, stated that the country would eventually return to the contest, with a cost assessment as a prerequisite.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eurovoix.com/2019/11/20/andorra-rtva-to-return-to-the-eurovision-song-contest/ |title=Andorra: Government Plans for RTVA's Return to Eurovision Song Contest |first=Anthony |last=Granger |date=20 November 2019 |website=Eurovoix |access-date=23 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191123101846/https://eurovoix.com/2019/11/20/andorra-rtva-to-return-to-the-eurovision-song-contest/ |archive-date=23 November 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* {{Esc|Latvia}} \u2013 In March 2020, [[Latvijas Telev\u012bzija]] announced that they will make a decision on their participation in the contest after the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Latvia|Covid-19 outbreak]] passes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://escxtra.com/2020/03/27/ltv-eurovision-2021/ |title=\ud83c\uddf1\ud83c\uddfb LTV to make decision on Eurovision 2021 participation after Covid-19 outbreak |first=Tom |last=Ryan |date=27 March 2020 |website=ESCXtra |access-date=27 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327143956/https://escxtra.com/2020/03/27/ltv-eurovision-2021/ |archive-date=27 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* {{Esc|Morocco}} \u2013 In response to rumours that the EBU had been in discussions with Morocco regarding participation in the contest, Karim Sbai, the Director of Communications of Morocco's [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Nationale de Radiodiffusion et de T\u00e9l\u00e9vision]] (SNRT), stated in February 2020 that Morocco's possible return to the contest has not yet been discussed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eurovoix.com/2020/02/01/morocco-snrt-spokesperson-unaware-of-any-discussions-regarding-eurovision/ |title=Morocco: SNRT Spokesperson Unaware of Any Discussions Regarding Eurovision |last=Granger |first=Anthony |date=1 February 2020 |website=Eurovoix |access-date=1 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201173727/https://eurovoix.com/2020/02/01/morocco-snrt-spokesperson-unaware-of-any-discussions-regarding-eurovision/ |archive-date=1 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* {{Esc|Portugal}} \u2013 In March 2020, [[Elisa Silva|Elisa]], who had been selected to represent {{Esccnty|Portugal|y=2020}} in the 2020 contest, stated that she would not be internally selected by [[R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal]] to represent Portugal in 2021.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://escxtra.com/2020/03/23/elisa-no-return-2021/ |title=\ud83c\uddf5\ud83c\uddf9 Elisa will not be internally selected by RTP for 2021 |first=Tom |last=Ryan |date=23 March 2020 |website=ESCXtra |access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Associate EBU members ===\n* {{Esc|United States}} \u2013 In January 2020, the EBU said that it would evaluate the United States participating in the contest if the upcoming [[American Song Contest]] became a success. Several broadcasters in the United States are associate members of the EBU.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://escxtra.com/2020/01/16/ebu-discuss-united-states-eurovision/ |title=\ud83c\uddfa\ud83c\uddf8 EBU will \"look at\" United States participation in Eurovision if American Song Contest is a success |first=Ryan |last=Cobb |date=16 January 2020 |website=ESCXtra |access-date=3 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229131838/https://escxtra.com/2020/01/16/ebu-discuss-united-states-eurovision/ |archive-date=29 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://eurovision.tv/}}\n\n{{Eurovision Song Contest}}\n\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest 2021| ]]\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest by year|2021]]\n[[Category:Scheduled events]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox song contest\n| name = Eurovision Song Contest\n| year = 2021\n| logo = Eurovision Song Contest.svg\n| semi1 = \n| semi2 = \n| final = \n| presenters = \n| director = \n| exsupervisor = [[Martin \u00d6sterdahl]]\n| producer = \n| writer = \n| winner = \n| vote = \n| host = \n| venue = \n| entries = <!-- Reserve this field for when the final list of participants is announced by the EBU -->\n| debut = <!-- Reserve this field for when the final list of participants is announced by the EBU -->\n| return = <!-- Reserve this field for when the final list of participants is announced by the EBU -->\n| nonreturn = <!-- Reserve this field for when the final list of participants is announced by the EBU -->\n| null = \n| interval = \n| opening = \n<!-- Map Legend Colours \u2013 Please do not add country names to this section, it will not change the map. -->\n| Green = \n| Green SA = Y\n| Purple = Y\n| Red = \n| Yellow = Y\n}}\n\nThe '''Eurovision Song Contest 2021''' is set to be the 65th edition of the [[Eurovision Song Contest]]. Following the cancellation of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2020]], the organising [[European Broadcasting Union]] (EBU) is discussing carryovers from the 2020 contest, such as host city and participating artists, with various parties.\n\n== Format ==\n\n=== Location ===\nFollowing the cancellation of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2020]], the organising [[European Broadcasting Union]] (EBU) is in talks with Dutch broadcasters [[AVROTROS]], [[Nederlandse Publieke Omroep (organization)|NPO]] and [[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting|NOS]], as well as the city of [[Rotterdam]], which were to organise the 2020 contest, on the possibility of staging the 2021 contest in the city.<ref name=\"2020 cancellation statement\">{{cite web |url=https://eurovision.tv/official-ebu-statement-and-faq-eurovision-song-contest-2020-cancellation |title=Official EBU statement & FAQ on Eurovision 2020 cancellation |date=18 March 2020 |website=[[Eurovision.tv]] |access-date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318142008/https://eurovision.tv/official-ebu-statement-and-faq-eurovision-song-contest-2020-cancellation |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Executive supervisor ===\nIn January 2020, the EBU announced that [[Martin \u00d6sterdahl]] would become the executive supervisor for the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] after the 2020 edition, succeeding [[Jon Ola Sand]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eurovision.tv/story/martin-osterdahl-new-eurovision-song-contest-executive-supervisor |title=Martin \u00d6sterdahl new Eurovision Song Contest Executive Supervisor |date=20 January 2020 |website=[[Eurovision.tv]]}}</ref> Before his appointment, \u00d6sterdahl had been an [[executive producer]] for the {{Escyr|2013}} and {{Escyr|2016}} editions, and had been a member of the Eurovision Song Contest reference group between 2012 and 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eurovoix.com/2020/01/20/martin-osterdahl-appointed-eurovision-executive-supervisor/ |title=Martin \u00d6sterdahl Appointed Eurovision Executive Supervisor |first=Neil |last=Farren |date=20 January 2020 |website=Eurovoix |access-date=20 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318204303/https://eurovoix.com/2020/01/20/martin-osterdahl-appointed-eurovision-executive-supervisor/ |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Entries ===\nFollowing the cancellation of the 2020 contest, the EBU explored the option of allowing the songs selected for the 2020 contest to compete in the 2021 contest, which would need to be discussed with the Eurovision Song Contest reference group and the national broadcasters.<ref name=\"2020 cancellation statement\" /> [[Victoria Georgieva|Victoria]], the planned participant for Bulgaria in 2020, publicly expressed her support for such a move.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eurovisionworld.com/esc/the-favorit-to-win-eurovision-2020-we-should-be-allowed-to-perform-our-songs-in-2021 |title=The favourite to win Eurovision 2020: \"We should be allowed to perform our songs in 2021\" |author=Rasmus |date=18 March 2020 |website=Eurovisionworld |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320102431/https://eurovisionworld.com/esc/the-favorit-to-win-eurovision-2020-we-should-be-allowed-to-perform-our-songs-in-2021 |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> However, on 20 March 2020, the reference group decided that, in accordance with the [[rules of the Eurovision Song Contest]], the 2020 songs would not be eligible to compete in the 2021 contest.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eurovision.tv/story/intention-to-honour-eurovision-2020-songs-artists |title=Intention to honour Eurovision 2020 songs and artists |date=20 March 2020 |website=[[Eurovision.tv]] |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320195055/https://eurovision.tv/story/intention-to-honour-eurovision-2020-songs-artists |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Opening and interval acts ===\n[[Lenny Kuhr]], one of the winners of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1969]], stated she would perform at the 2021 contest. She was previously slated to perform in the 2020 edition before it was cancelled.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=LenKuhr |number=1242239936658649094 |title=Ik doe ook weer mee op Eurovision 2021 in Rotterdam! Bijna alle concerten die in maart, april en mei niet door konden gaan zijn verplaatst naar volgend seizoen. Houdt anderhalve meter afstand dan komt alles goed. |first=Lenny |last=Kuhr |author-link=Lenny Kuhr |date=24 March 2020 |language=nl}}</ref>\n\n== Participating countries ==\n\n=== Returning artists ===\nAfter the cancellation of the 2020 contest, multiple participating broadcasters announced that for the 2021 contest they would internally select the same artists initially selected for 2020: Australia, Austria, Azerbaijan, Belgium, Bulgaria, Georgia, Greece, Israel, Netherlands, Romania, Spain, Switzerland and Ukraine.<ref name=\"confirmed_2020artists\">{{cite web |url=https://eurovision.tv/story/these-artists-are-already-confirmed-for-eurovision-2021 |title=These artists are already confirmed for Eurovision 2021 |date=23 March 2020 |website=[[Eurovision.tv]] |access-date=23 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323182536/https://eurovision.tv/story/these-artists-are-already-confirmed-for-eurovision-2021 |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Stefania Liberakakis|Stefania]] represented the {{Esccnty|Netherlands|Junior|y=2016}} in the [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2016]] as part of the group [[Netherlands in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2016#Kisses|Kisses]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://wiwibloggs.com/2020/02/03/confirmed-stefania-represent-greece-eurovision-2020-supergirl/249074/ |title=Confirmed! Stefania will represent Greece at Eurovision 2020 with \"SUPERGIRL\" |first=Robyn |last=Gallagher |date=3 February 2020 |website=[[Wiwibloggs]] |access-date=3 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203195452/https://wiwibloggs.com/2020/02/03/confirmed-stefania-represent-greece-eurovision-2020-supergirl/249074/ |archive-date=3 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Vincent Bueno]] provided backing vocals for [[Nathan Trent]] for {{Esccnty|Austria|y=2017}} in {{Escyr|2017}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://escxtra.com/2020/03/26/vincent-bueno-2021/ |title=\ud83c\udde6\ud83c\uddf9 Vincent Bueno to return to represent Austria in 2021 |first=Tom |last=Ryan |date=26 March 2020 |website=ESCXtra |access-date=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326154809/https://escxtra.com/2020/03/26/vincent-bueno-2021/ |archive-date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Provisional list of participating countries ===\nThe following countries have confirmed their intent to participate in the 2021 contest.\n<!--Please do not add confirmations that took place before 18 March because of the unique situation concerning the cancellation of Eurovision 2020 -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Country\n! Artist<ref name=\"confirmed_2020artists\" />\n! Song\n! Language(s)\n|-\n| {{Esc|Australia}}\n| [[Montaigne (musician)|Montaigne]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sbs.com.au/programs/eurovision/article/2020/04/01/montaigne-represent-australia-eurovision-song-contest-2021 |title=Montaigne to represent Australia at the Eurovision Song Contest 2021 |date=2 April 2020 |website=[[Special Broadcasting Service]] |access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Austria}}\n| [[Vincent Bueno]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eurovoix.com/2020/03/26/austria-vincent-bueno-eurovision/ |title=Austria: Vincent Bueno to Eurovision 2021 |first=Emily |last=Herbert |date=26 March 2020 |website=Eurovoix |access-date=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326143507/https://eurovoix.com/2020/03/26/austria-vincent-bueno-eurovision/ |archive-date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Azerbaijan}}\n| [[Samira Efendi|Efendi]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Belgium}}\n| [[Hooverphonic]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Bulgaria}}\n| [[Victoria Georgieva|Victoria]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Croatia}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://hrtprikazuje.hrt.hr/593786/za-eurosong-2021-morat-ce-biti-odabrane-nove-pjesme |title=Za Eurosong 2021. morat \u0107e biti odabrane nove pjesme |language=hr |author=Komunikacije HRT-a |date=21 March 2020 |website=[[Hrvatska radiotelevizija]] |access-date=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321131742/https://hrtprikazuje.hrt.hr/593786/za-eurosong-2021-morat-ce-biti-odabrane-nove-pjesme |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Denmark}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dr.dk/musik/foerst-blev-eurovision-aflyst-nu-kommer-der-alligevel-et-show |title=F\u00f8rst blev Eurovision aflyst. Nu kommer der alligevel et show |language=da |first1=Kasper |last1=Madsb\u00f8ll Christensen |first2=Christian |last2=Mejdahl |date=3 April 2020 |website=[[Danmarks Radio]] |access-date=3 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321131742/https://www.dr.dk/musik/foerst-blev-eurovision-aflyst-nu-kommer-der-alligevel-et-show |archive-date=3 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Estonia}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eurovoix.com/2020/03/18/estonia-eesti-laul-will-determine-eurovision-2021-participant/ |title=Estonia: Eesti Laul Will Determine Eurovision 2021 Participant |first=Anthony |last=Granger |date=18 March 2020 |website=Eurovoix |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320102154/https://eurovoix.com/2020/03/18/estonia-eesti-laul-will-determine-eurovision-2021-participant/ |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Finland}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://esctoday.com/179527/finland-yle-confirms-participation-in-eurovision-2021-umk-2021-confirmed/ |title=Finland: YLE confirms participation in Eurovision 2021; UMK 2021 confirmed |first=Sanjay (Sergio) |last=Jiandani |date=25 March 2020 |website=ESCToday |access-date=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326113843/http://esctoday.com/179527/finland-yle-confirms-participation-in-eurovision-2021-umk-2021-confirmed/ |archive-date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Georgia}}\n| [[Tornike Kipiani]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Greece}}\n| [[Stefania Liberakakis|Stefania]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Ireland}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://escxtra.com/2020/03/21/ireland-eurovision-2021/ |title=RT\u00c9 confirm intentions to take part in Eurovision 2021 |first=Tom |last=Ryan |date=21 March 2020 |website=ESCXtra |access-date=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321124945/https://escxtra.com/2020/03/21/ireland-eurovision-2021/ |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Israel}}\n| [[Eden Alene]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Lithuania}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lrt.lt/en/news-in-english/19/1157011/lithuania-to-pick-new-song-for-next-year-s-eurovision |title=Lithuania to pick new song for next year's Eurovision |date=31 March 2020 |website=[[Lithuanian National Radio and Television]]}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Netherlands}}\n| [[Jeangu Macrooy]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Norway}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://esctoday.com/179543/norway-nrk-confirms-participation-in-eurovision-2021-mgp-confirmed/ |title=Norway: NRK confirms participation in Eurovision 2021: MGP confirmed |first=Sanjay |last=Jiandani |date=26 March 2020 |website=ESCToday |access-date=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326113838/http://esctoday.com/179543/norway-nrk-confirms-participation-in-eurovision-2021-mgp-confirmed/ |archive-date=26 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Romania}}\n| [[Roxen (singer)|Roxen]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://esctoday.com/179596/romania-tvr-confirms-roxen-as-2021-romanian-eurovision-hopeful/ |title=Romania: TVR confirms Roxen as 2021 Romanian Eurovision hopeful |first=Sanjay |last=Jiandani |date=31 March 2020 |website=ESCToday}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Spain}}\n| [[Blas Cant\u00f3]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Sweden}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eurovisionworld.com/esc/sweden-2021-new-representative-to-be-selected-from-melodifestivalen/ |title=Sweden: New artist and song to be selected from Melodifestivalen 2021 |first=Steven |last=Spiteri |date=18 March 2020 |website=Eurovisionworld}}</ref>\n| \n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Switzerland}}\n| [[Gjon's Tears]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{Esc|Ukraine}}\n| [[Go_A]]\n|\n|\n|}\n\n== Other countries ==\n{{Further|List of countries in the Eurovision Song Contest}}\nEligibility for potential participation in the Eurovision Song Contest requires a national broadcaster with [[European Broadcasting Union#Members|active EBU membership]] that will be able to broadcast the contest via the [[Eurovision (network)|Eurovision network]]. The EBU will issue an invitation of participation in the contest to all active members. In contrast to previous years, associate member {{Esccnty|Australia}} does not need an invitation for the 2021 contest, as it had previously been granted permission to participate at least until 2023.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovision.tv/story/australia-secures-spot-in-eurovision-until-2023|title=Australia secures spot in Eurovision for the next five years|last=Groot|first=Evert|date=12 February 2019|website=[[Eurovision.tv]]|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190213045839/https://eurovision.tv/story/australia-secures-spot-in-eurovision-until-2023|archive-date=13 February 2019|access-date=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Active EBU members ===\n* {{Esc|Andorra}} \u2013 In November 2019, [[Democrats for Andorra]], the ruling party of Andorra, stated that the country would eventually return to the contest, with a cost assessment as a prerequisite.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eurovoix.com/2019/11/20/andorra-rtva-to-return-to-the-eurovision-song-contest/ |title=Andorra: Government Plans for RTVA's Return to Eurovision Song Contest |first=Anthony |last=Granger |date=20 November 2019 |website=Eurovoix |access-date=23 January 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191123101846/https://eurovoix.com/2019/11/20/andorra-rtva-to-return-to-the-eurovision-song-contest/ |archive-date=23 November 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* {{Esc|Latvia}} \u2013 In March 2020, [[Latvijas Telev\u012bzija]] announced that they will make a decision on their participation in the contest after the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Latvia|Covid-19 outbreak]] passes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://escxtra.com/2020/03/27/ltv-eurovision-2021/ |title=\ud83c\uddf1\ud83c\uddfb LTV to make decision on Eurovision 2021 participation after Covid-19 outbreak |first=Tom |last=Ryan |date=27 March 2020 |website=ESCXtra |access-date=27 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327143956/https://escxtra.com/2020/03/27/ltv-eurovision-2021/ |archive-date=27 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* {{Esc|Morocco}} \u2013 In response to rumours that the EBU had been in discussions with Morocco regarding participation in the contest, Karim Sbai, the Director of Communications of Morocco's [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Nationale de Radiodiffusion et de T\u00e9l\u00e9vision]] (SNRT), stated in February 2020 that Morocco's possible return to the contest has not yet been discussed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://eurovoix.com/2020/02/01/morocco-snrt-spokesperson-unaware-of-any-discussions-regarding-eurovision/ |title=Morocco: SNRT Spokesperson Unaware of Any Discussions Regarding Eurovision |last=Granger |first=Anthony |date=1 February 2020 |website=Eurovoix |access-date=1 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201173727/https://eurovoix.com/2020/02/01/morocco-snrt-spokesperson-unaware-of-any-discussions-regarding-eurovision/ |archive-date=1 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* {{Esc|Portugal}} \u2013 In March 2020, [[Elisa Silva|Elisa]], who had been selected to represent {{Esccnty|Portugal|y=2020}} in the 2020 contest, stated that she would not be internally selected by [[R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal]] to represent Portugal in 2021.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://escxtra.com/2020/03/23/elisa-no-return-2021/ |title=\ud83c\uddf5\ud83c\uddf9 Elisa will not be internally selected by RTP for 2021 |first=Tom |last=Ryan |date=23 March 2020 |website=ESCXtra |access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Associate EBU members ===\n* {{Esc|United States}} \u2013 In January 2020, the EBU said that it would evaluate the United States participating in the contest if the upcoming [[American Song Contest]] became a success. Several broadcasters in the United States are associate members of the EBU.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://escxtra.com/2020/01/16/ebu-discuss-united-states-eurovision/ |title=\ud83c\uddfa\ud83c\uddf8 EBU will \"look at\" United States participation in Eurovision if American Song Contest is a success |first=Ryan |last=Cobb |date=16 January 2020 |website=ESCXtra |access-date=3 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229131838/https://escxtra.com/2020/01/16/ebu-discuss-united-states-eurovision/ |archive-date=29 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://eurovision.tv/}}\n\n{{Eurovision Song Contest}}\n\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest 2021| ]]\n[[Category:Eurovision Song Contest by year|2021]]\n[[Category:Scheduled events]]\n", "name_user": "Youngandold", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eurovision_Song_Contest_2021"}
